    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Spirit of Neighborliness</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Bette Dewing letter comments on April 22 article about increasing youthfulness of co-op and condominium board members</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As an elder shareholder tenant in our co-op and a former four-term board member, I am troubled, not by the youthfulness of ''The New Kids on the Board'' (April 22) so much, but by some of these new members' seeming unconcern with the building's history and continuity.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As an elder shareholder tenant in our co-op and a former four-term board member, I am troubled, not by the youthfulness of ''The New Kids on the Board'' (April 22) so much, but by some of these new members' seeming unconcern with the building's history and continuity.</p>
        <p>Our proprietary lease begins with the statement, ''The primary purpose of this corporation is to provide homes.''</p>
        <p>I want board members, whatever their age or background, who feel strongly about the quality of life in their co-op or condo. This surely is helped along by creating a spirit of unobtrusive neighborliness.</p>
        <p>Older residents, especially those living alone, usually want, even need, these elements, more than younger ones or families do.</p>
        <p>Bette Dewing  Upper East Side</p>
      </block>
